14. Fourth Question. What Law is to be deemed so unjust that not only it does not oblige, but that it is not allowable to obey it?

We answer by explaining the kinds of InJustice which may affect Laws.

1. A Law may be unjust on the part of the Efficient Cause, the maker3 being made by one who has no due authority. Here is a defect of Commutative Justice, because the Maker of the Law assumes more than belongs to him. Such a Law does not oblige3 but the subject, if he ple-ase, may waive his right and obey.

2. A Law may be unjust with regard to the Final Cause, as for instance, if it do not tend to the public good, nor respect the rights of the community.
